## Product surfaces

The app has three tabs in a bottom navigation bar. These are the only top-level navigation destinations.

### Discover (Tab 1 — Compass icon)

The primary surface. This is where flow 1 and flow 2 play out for consumers.

**Header:**
- City name displayed prominently, tappable to open city switcher
- Switching cities fully refreshes all content across all tabs

**Filter rows:**
- Row 1 (time) and Row 2 (category) as described in flow 1, step 1
- Filters are sticky at the top as the user scrolls

**Feed sections (browse mode — no time filter active):**

The feed is a vertically scrollable page with content organized into sections. The sections are:

1. **Events and spots** — the main content. Cards interleaved in a single stream, ordered by editorial quality and trust signals. This is not a separate section with a header — it is the primary body of the feed with other sections interspersed.

2. **From Friends** — appears when the user has approved followers who have saved items in the current city. Shows a section header ("From people you trust"), then a horizontal scroll of cards with friend attribution: the friend's colored avatar, their name, and "saved this." Each card shows the spot or event they saved. Tapping a card opens the item detail. This section only appears if there are relevant friend saves to show.

3. **People to follow** — horizontal scroll of user avatars with names and short context (e.g., "42 saves in Barcelona"). These are users with active public collections in the current city. Tapping an avatar opens their profile.

4. **Public collections** — horizontal scroll of collection cards from various users. Each card shows cover image, name, creator, and save count. Tapping opens the collection.

**Feed behavior (planning mode — time filter active):**
When a time filter is selected, the same sections exist but their ordering and content changes:
- Time-relevant events move to the top of the feed
- Spots that are time-relevant (pop-ups, seasonal menus, limited-run exhibitions) also rise
- The "From Friends" section filters to only show items relevant to the selected time
- Evergreen content (permanent spots, general collections, people to follow) moves below or is deprioritized
- The featured collection is shown if time-relevant, otherwise deprioritized

**Search:**
A search bar is accessible from the discover feed. Searching queries across users, spots, events, and collections simultaneously. Results are grouped by type. Minimum viable implementation: keyword matching on names and descriptions.

---

### Map (Tab 2 — Map icon)

A spatial view of the same content available in the discover feed. The map is not a separate data source — it renders the same spots and events, filtered by the same active filters.

**Map view:**
- Full-screen map centered on the user's current city
- **iOS implementation:** Spots and events both use **teal** (`portalPrimary`) capsule pins; **events** show a **`ticket.fill`** icon plus title, **spots** show **`mappin`** plus name (icon distinguishes type).
- **Legacy PRD copy:** dark spot pins and orange event pins — superseded on iOS by the unified teal + icon treatment (see `PRD-UI-DESIGN-REVIEW.md`).
- Live/ongoing events (start time ≤ now < end time) display a small **"LIVE"** badge on the event pin
- Layer toggle at the top: All / Spots / Events — allows the user to show only one content type

**Filters:**
The same time and category filters from the discover feed are available on the map. Filter state is shared across discover and map — changing a filter on one tab affects the other.

**Interaction:**
- Tap a pin → a card preview slides in at the top of the screen showing: name, neighborhood, time (if event), save count, and creator attribution
- Tap the card preview → opens the full detail screen as an overlay
- Save button is available directly on the card preview — one tap to save without opening the detail screen

**Recenter:**
A recenter button returns the map to the user's current location or the city center.

---

### Profile (Tab 3 — User icon)

The user's home base. Where saves, collections, and created content live. Also the entry point for flow 3 (creation).

**Own profile layout:**

- **Header:** Avatar (initial letter on colored background), name, handle, current city
- **Stats:** Saved count, collections count, following count

- **My Saves:** A list of all items the user has saved, in reverse chronological order (most recent save first). Each item shows the same card treatment as the feed. Tapping opens the detail screen. This is the user's raw, unsorted shortlist — the output of flow 1, step 4.

- **My Collections:** A list of the user's created collections. Each collection shows: name, visibility badge (Private / Friends / Public), item count, and cover image. Tapping a collection opens it to show its contents. A "Create collection" action is available here. See the Collections section below for full mechanics.

- **My Events:** A list of events where this user is a host. Each shows the event card. A "+" button allows creating a new event (flow 3 entry point). Spot creation is available from the Profile create actions; in the early version there is no "My Spots" owner list — anyone can add spots.

- **Followers / Following:** Tappable follower and following counts open a screen showing the list of followers (with pending follow requests and accept/decline) and the list of users the current user follows. Tapping a user opens their profile.

**Viewing another user's profile:**

Accessible by tapping any user attribution (on a card, in a collection, in search results, in the "People to follow" section).

- **Header:** Avatar, name, handle, follower count, bio
- **Follow button:** Three states — "Follow" (not following), "Requested" (pending approval), "Following" (approved). Tapping "Follow" sends a request. Tapping "Following" unfollows.
- **Public collections:** Displayed as cards, always visible to anyone regardless of follow status
- **Spots owned:** Spots where this user is an owner. Visible to anyone.
- **Events hosted:** Events where this user is a host. Visible to anyone.
- **Saved items:** Visible only if the viewer is an approved follower. If not approved, this section shows a locked empty state with a brief explanation ("Follow [name] to see their saves").

This unified profile structure means a restaurant, a food blogger, and a casual user all look the same. The content on their profile — owned spots, curated collections, or hosted events — communicates what kind of user they are without explicit labels or badges.

